Pacotes necessários

Para este tutorial nós iremos utilizar funções dos seguintes pacotes:

BAMM

Para mais informações sobre o BAMM ver:

http://bamm-project.org/index.html

Preparando o config

Antes de rodar o BAMM é preciso criar um arquivo de configuração.

### Mude o seu working directory

setwd("~/Post-doc-Unicamp/Bioinformatica/Aulas/10 - Diversificação")
getwd() -> wd

### Importar a árvore

tree.file = "Lychnophora_newick.tre"

read.tree(tree.file) -> tree

### Gerar um arquivo com sampling probabilities

nodes <- c(29, 20)
names(nodes) <- c("Clade_A", "Clade_B")
probs <- c(1, 0.05)

samp.probs <- data.frame(spp=tree$tip.label, clade=NA, probs=NA)

for (i in 1:length(nodes)) {
  descendants(tree, node = nodes[i], labels=T) -> spp0
  match(spp0, samp.probs$spp) -> m0
  samp.probs[m0,2] <- names(nodes)[i]
  samp.probs[m0,3] <- probs[i]
}

samp.probs

### Gerar priors

priors <- setBAMMpriors(tree, outfile = NULL)

### Gerar o control file

n = "1000000"
freq="2000"
exp.n.shifts = as.numeric(priors["expectedNumberOfShifts"])

generateControlFile(file = 'BAMM_divcontrol.txt', type="diversification", params = list(treefile = tree.file, useGlobalSamplingProbability = '0', numberOfGenerations = n, overwrite = '1', lambdaInitPrior = as.numeric(priors['lambdaInitPrior']), lambdaShiftPrior = as.numeric(priors['lambdaShiftPrior']),  muInitPrior = as.numeric(priors['muInitPrior']), expectedNumberOfShifts = exp.n.shifts, eventDataWriteFreq=freq))

Executar

É possível executar programas externos dentro do R.

call <- "bamm -c BAMM_divcontrol.txt"
system(call)

Comparando modelos (ML)

lik1 <- make.bisse(tree, habit, sampling.f=missing.probs) 
lik2 <- constrain(lik1, lambda0 ~ lambda1) 
lik3 <- constrain(lik1, mu0 ~ mu1)
lik4 <- constrain(lik1, q01 ~ q10)
lik5 <- constrain(lik1, lambda0 ~ lambda1, q01 ~ q10)
lik6 <- constrain(lik1, lambda0 ~ lambda1, mu0 ~ mu1, q01 ~ q10)


p <- starting.point.bisse(tree)
ml1 <- find.mle(lik1, x.init=p)
p1 <- coef(ml1)

ml2 <- find.mle(lik2, x.init=p1[argnames(lik2)])
p2 <- coef(ml2)

ml3 <- find.mle(lik3, x.init=p1[argnames(lik3)])
p3 <- coef(ml3)

ml4 <- find.mle(lik4, x.init=p1[argnames(lik4)])
p4 <- coef(ml4)

ml5 <- find.mle(lik5, x.init=p1[argnames(lik5)])
p5 <- coef(ml5)

ml6 <- find.mle(lik6, x.init=p1[argnames(lik6)])
p6 <- coef(ml6)

anova(ml1, eq.spec=ml2, eq.ext=ml3, eq.trans=ml4, eq.spec.trans=ml5, all.equal=ml6) -> anova.t

Estimando parâmetros (Bayesian)

### Make bisse - Full model

nsteps = 10000

p <- starting.point.bisse(tree)

lik1 <- make.bisse(tree, habit, sampling.f=missing.probs) 
ml1 <- find.mle(lik1, p)
p1 <- coef(ml1)
prior <- make.prior.exponential(1/2)
tmp <- mcmc(lik1, p1, nsteps=1000, prior=prior, w=1, print.every=10)
w <- diff(sapply(tmp[2:7], quantile, c(0.025, 0.975)))
mcmc2 <- mcmc(lik1, p1, nsteps=nsteps, prior=prior, w=w, print.every=10)
### Trace

mcmc2 -> x
plot(x$p ~ x$i, type="l")
title("BiSSE - Fruit type")

burnin = 1000

mcmc2[-c(1:match(burnin, mcmc2$i)),] -> mcmc.b
mcmc.b -> x
plot(x$p ~ x$i, type="l")
title("BiSSE - Fruit type")

effectiveSize(mcmc.b$p)
##     var1 
## 1242.255

Plot

### lambda0 = speciation state 0
### lambda1 = speciation state 1
### mu0 = extinction state 0
### mu1 = extinction from region B
### q01 = transition from 0 to 1
### q10 = transition from 1 to 0

mcmc.b[c("lambda0", "lambda1")] -> lambda
mcmc.b[c("mu0", "mu1")] -> mu
mcmc.b[c("q01", "q10")] -> q
lambda -> net
net[,1] <- lambda[,1] - mu[,1]
net[,2] <- lambda[,2] - mu[,2]
colnames(net) <- colnames(mu) <- colnames(lambda) <- c("Arbusto", "Arvoreta")
colnames(q) <- c("Arbusto para arvoreta", "Arvoreta para arbusto")

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
profiles.plot(net, col.line=morpho.cols, las=1, xlab="Net diversification", legend="topleft")
profiles.plot(lambda, col.line=morpho.cols, las=1, xlab="Speciation rate", legend="topright")
profiles.plot(mu, col.line=morpho.cols, las=1, xlab="Extinction rate", legend="topright")
profiles.plot(q, col.line=morpho.cols, las=1, xlab="Transitions rate", legend="topright")

HiSSE

Para mais detalhes sobre HiSSE ver:

https://www.zoology.ubc.ca/prog/diversitree/doc/diversitree-tutorial.pdf https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/hisse/vignettes/hisse-vignette.pdf

### Turnover.anc
### Default = c(1,1,0,0) = This means for state 0 and state 1, 
### we are allowing one free parameter to define the net turnover 
### rate (birth+death) in the model. This is essentially a BiSSE.

### c(1,2,3,0) =  model with three turnover rates, where we 
### include a free parameter for a hidden state associated with state 0

### c(1,2,0,3) = model with three turnover rates, where we 
### include a free parameter for a hidden state associated with state 1

### c(1,2,3,4) =  full model, four separate net turnover rates, 
### for states 0A (first entry), 1A (second entry), 0B (third entry), 
### and 1B (fourth entry).

hisse.dat <- data.frame(spp=names(habit), habit)
output.type="net.div"

## Fit BiSSE equivalent

turnover.anc=c(1,2,0,0)
eps.anc=c(1,2,0,0)
trans.rates.bisse <- TransMatMaker(hidden.states=FALSE)
trans.rates.bisse
##     (0) (1)
## (0)  NA   2
## (1)   1  NA
pp.bisse <- hisse(tree, hisse.dat, hidden.states=FALSE, f=missing.probs, turnover.anc=turnover.anc, eps.anc=eps.anc, trans.rate=trans.rates.bisse, output.type=output.type)
## Initializing... 
## Finished. Beginning bounded subplex routine... 
## Finished. Summarizing results...
## Fit the 2-state character-independent (CID-2) model
## the goal is to set up a model where the diversification 
## process is independent from the observed states (0 or 1) 
## of the focal trait. In other words, diversification rate 
## differences, if they exist, will only be associated with 
## one of the hidden states (A or B) regardless of the state
## of the focal trait
## Rates = all equal

turnover.anc = c(1,1,2,2)
eps.anc = c(1,1,2,2)
trans.rates.hisse.c2 = TransMatMaker(hidden.states=TRUE)
trans.rates.hisse.c2 = ParDrop(trans.rates.hisse.c2, c(3,5,8,10))
trans.rates.hisse.c2
##      (0A) (1A) (0B) (1B)
## (0A)   NA    3    5    0
## (1A)    1   NA    0    7
## (0B)    2    0   NA    8
## (1B)    0    4    6   NA
pp.hisse.c2 <- hisse(tree, hisse.dat, f=missing.probs, hidden.states=TRUE, turnover.anc=turnover.anc, eps.anc=eps.anc, trans.rate=trans.rates.hisse.c2, output.type=output.type)
## Initializing... 
## Finished. Beginning bounded subplex routine... 
## Finished. Summarizing results...
## Fit HiSSE full

turnover.anc=c(1,2,3,4)
eps.anc=c(1,2,3,4)
trans.rates.hisse <- TransMatMaker(hidden.states=TRUE)
trans.rates.hisse <- ParDrop(trans.rates.hisse, c(3,5,8,10))
trans.rates.hisse
##      (0A) (1A) (0B) (1B)
## (0A)   NA    3    5    0
## (1A)    1   NA    0    7
## (0B)    2    0   NA    8
## (1B)    0    4    6   NA
pp.hisse <- hisse(tree, hisse.dat, hidden.states=TRUE, f=missing.probs, turnover.anc=turnover.anc, 
                    eps.anc=eps.anc, trans.rate=trans.rates.hisse, output.type=output.type)

## Finished. Beginning bounded subplex routine... 
## Finished. Summarizing results...
### Summary

hisse.models <- list(bisse=pp.bisse, cid2=pp.hisse.c2, hisse=pp.hisse)

unlist(lapply(hisse.models, "[", "loglik")) -> lnl

## X1 X2

### Sampling probs

both.sampling = 0.8
area1.sampling = 0.8
area2.sampling = 0.8

missing.probs <- c(both.sampling, area1.sampling, area1.sampling)

### Areas states

# 0 = widespread
# 1 = endemic of "Espinhaço"
# 2 = endemic of "Diamantina"

states <- vector(length=nrow(areas.t))
names(states) <- rownames(areas.t)

for (i in 1:nrow(areas.t)) {
  areas.t[i,] -> a0
  sum(a0) -> s0
  if (s0 == 1) {
    which(a0 == 1) -> states[i]
  } else {
    states[i] <- 0
  }
}

Comparando modelos (ML)

### Comparando diferentes cenários

lik1 <- make.geosse(tree, states, sampling.f=missing.probs) ## full
lik2 <- constrain(lik1, sA ~ sB, sAB ~ 0) 
lik3 <- constrain(lik1, xA ~ xB)
lik4 <- constrain(lik1, dA ~ dB)

### ML

p <- starting.point.geosse(tree)
ml1 <- find.mle(lik1, p)
p <- coef(ml1)

ml1 <- find.mle(lik1, p)
ml2 <- find.mle(lik2, p[argnames(lik2)])
ml3 <- find.mle(lik3, p[argnames(lik3)])
ml4 <- find.mle(lik4, p[argnames(lik4)])

anova(ml1, eq.spec=ml2, eq.ext=ml3, eq.disp=ml4) -> anova.t

BAMM phenotypic

Para mais informações sobre o BAMM ver:

http://bamm-project.org/quickstart.html#phenotypic-evolution

Preparando o config

Antes de rodar o BAMM é preciso criar um arquivo de configuração.

### Importar a árvore

tree.file = "Lychnophora_newick.tre"

read.tree(tree.file) -> tree

### Importar os dados fenotípicos

read.table("Lychnophora_clim_pca.txt", header = T) -> pca.clim
data.frame(spp=rownames(pca.clim), pheno=pca.clim$Axis1) -> pheno.dat


pheno.file = "Lychnophora_clim_1.txt"

write.table(pheno.dat, pheno.file, row.names = F, col.names = F, sep="\t", quote = F)

### contMap

pheno.dat$pheno -> c.dat
names(c.dat) <- pheno.dat$spp

contMap(tree, c.dat)

### Gerar priors

priors <- setBAMMpriors(tree, outfile = NULL, traits = pheno.file)

### Gerar o control file

n = "1000000"
freq="2000"
exp.n.shifts = as.numeric(priors["expectedNumberOfShifts"])

generateControlFile(file = 'BAMM_divcontrol_pheno.txt', type="trait", params = list(treefile = tree.file, traitfile=pheno.file, numberOfGenerations = n, overwrite = '1', betaInitPrior = as.numeric(priors['betaInitPrior']), betaShiftPrior = as.numeric(priors["betaShiftPrior"]), useObservedMinMaxAsTraitPriors = as.numeric(priors["useObservedMinMaxAsTraitPriors"]), eventDataWriteFreq=freq, mcmcOutfile = "mcmc_pheno_out.txt", eventDataOutfile = "event_data_pheno.txt"))
